1) Try to open firewall manager from system settings.
2) Try to open firewall manager from Kmenu.
3) Try to stop firewall service from the start/stop button of firewall manager.
    Type console
    # service list
    Observe that iptables service gets off.

4) Try to start service from the start/stop button of firewall manager.
    Type console
    # service list
    Observe that iptables service gets on.

5) Push th configuration button and try these actions for options: Limited Content Serving or Access Restriction
    5.a) Adding  port
    5.b) Removing port
    5.c) Taking up a port
    5.d) Taking down a port

Note: Observe the outputs of this command for each situation.
Type console
# iptables --list-rules

6) Limited content serving
     6.a) After adding a port from firewall manager.
        6.a.a) Enable limited content serving
            	Observe that the output of the above command contains these: 
            	-A PARDUS-IN-MOD-SERVING -p tcp -m multiport --dports <addedPORT> -j ACCEPT
            	-A PARDUS-IN-MOD-SERVING -p tcp -m multiport --dports 0:1024 -m tcp --tcp-flags FIN,SYN,RST,ACK SYN -j REJECT --reject-with icmp-port-unreachable
            	-A PARDUS-IN-MOD-SERVING -p udp -m multiport --dports 0:1024 -j REJECT --reject-with icmp-port-unreachable
        6.a.b) Disable limited content serving
            Observe that the above lines are removed from the output of the below command.
    6.b) Without adding a port
        Observe that the output of the above command contains these:
         -A PARDUS-IN-MOD-SERVING -p tcp -m multiport --dports 0:1024 -m tcp --tcp-flags FIN,SYN,RST,ACK SYN -j REJECT --reject-with icmp-port-unreachable
         -A PARDUS-IN-MOD-SERVING -p udp -m multiport --dports 0:1024 -j REJECT --reject-with icmp-port-unreachable


7) Internet sharing
    7.a) Enable Internet sharing
    	(If you have two internal ethernet card or an extra external ethernet card, you can test this part, if not skip 7.a.a)
        7.a.a) Select different values for gate to internet and gate to home network
            	Observe that the above command output contains these:
             	-A PARDUS-FW-MOD-SHARING -i <input> -o <output> -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT
             	-A PARDUS-FW-MOD-SHARING -i <output> -o <input> -j ACCEPT
             	-t nat -A PARDUS-POST-MOD-SHARING -o <input> -j MASQUERADE
        7.a.b) Give same values
            	Observe that the above lines are removed from the output of the below command.

8) Access Restriction 
    8.a) After adding a port from firewall manager.
        8.a.a) Enable Access Restriction
            Observe that the port is added
            There should be lines like below at output of the command:
            -A PARDUS-FW-MOD-BLOCK -p tcp -m multiport --dports <addedPORT> -j DROP
            -A PARDUS-OUT-MOD-BLOCK -p tcp -m multiport --dports <addedPORT> -j DROP
        - Disable Access RestrictionÂ·
            Observe that the above lines are removed from the output of the below command.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
- Pratical part of tests
    If the service openssh was disabled, start it from service manager.

    9) For Limited content serving: (If you have staic ip you can test it, if not skip it)
        9.a) Disable limited content serving
            - Try to make a remote connection from an other computer to your computer.
            	Type console
            	# ssh <your_computer_name>@<static_ip>
            	Observe that the connection accepted.

        9.b) Try to add a well known port and enable limited content serving.
            Open the related service of this port from service-manager.

            9.b.a) Try to make a remote connection from an other computer to your computer.
                # ssh <your_computer_name>@<static_ip>
                Observe that the connection refused.

            9.b.b) Try to make a remote connection using the added port from an other computer to your computer.
                # ssh -p <port> <your_computer_name>@<static_ip>
                Observe that the connection is accepted.

    10) For internet sharing:(If you have two internal ethernet card or an extra external ethernet card and an extra computer, you can test this part, if not skip it.)
        - Plug an extra external or internal ethernet card to your computer. And plug an ethernet cable between your computer and the other. ( And if the other computer have an internet acces please stop it. )
        - Enable internet sharing from firewall-manager.
        - Choose the first ethernet card for gate to internet, and the second for gate to home network.
            Now try to connect to connect internet over your computer and observe it.

    11) For access restriction:(If you have staic ip you can test it, if not skip it)
        11.a) Disable access restriction
            11.a.a) Try to make a remote connection with using a well known port from your computer to the other remote computer.
                If the remote computer has a static ip you can use it for remote connection

                Type console
                # ssh -p <port> <remote_computer_name>@<static_ip>
                Observe that the connection accepted.

            11.a.b) Try to add a well known port and enable access restriction.
            	- Try to make a remote connection using added port from your computer to the other computer.
                	# ssh -p <port> <remote_computer_name>@<static_ip>
                	Observe that the connection refused. 
